 To efficiently check if a number is a prime, we can implement a function in JavaScript that eliminates any non-prime numbers from the input array. Then, we can iterate through the prime numbers and print their numbers to the console. Here is the detailed implementation of this function: 
```
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) return false;
  for (let i = 2; i < num; i++) {
    if (num % i === 0) return false;
  }
  return true;
}
const array = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6];
const primeNumbers = [];
for (let i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
  if (isPrime(array[i])) {
    primeNumbers.push(array[i]);
  }
}
console.log(primeNumbers); // Output: [2, 3, 5, 11, 13]
```
This function efficiently checks if a number is prime and captures the unique prime numbers in the array for you.

